Sometimes people argue that insider trading is good. We want market prices =
to be accurate, to reflect all available information; that way the best pro=
jects will get financed and people will be able to buy and sell assets at=
=C2=A0prices that reflect their real values. Letting, say, corporate execut=
ives buy their stocks when they know good news is coming, or sell them when=
 they know bad news is coming, makes prices more accurate. So we should enc=
ourage it. That is the theory. You don=E2=80=99t hear it a lot these days a=
bout the stock market, but you do hear it sometimes. Here=E2=80=99s a recen=
t=C2=A0Planet Money episode=C2=A0halfheartedly making the case.
Outside=C2=A0of the stock market, though, this idea is more popular. =E2=80=
=9CIn boxing, it=E2=80=99s generally accepted =E2=80=94 if not condoned =E2=
=80=94 that [managers] sometimes bet on their fighters to win,=E2=80=9D the=
 Wall Street Journal=C2=A0noted last month, though other bets can lead to s=
uspicions of manipulation. Other sports sometimes have   stricter rules abo=
ut insider betting, but not always.
And people who set up=C2=A0prediction=C2=A0markets are more likely to=C2=A0=
argue that insider trading is good. The point of a prediction market is not=
 really to give people a good place to invest their retirement money; the p=
oint of a prediction market is to make accurate predictions. In the stock m=
arket, you=C2=A0want=C2=A0outsiders to feel comfortable that they can inves=
t their money and have a fair chance, and you might think that=E2=80=99s=C2=
=A0more important than price accuracy. In a prediction market, you don=E2=
=80=99t really care about fairness to outsiders at all; your goal is to get=
 a good prediction. You=E2=80=99d be totally happy with a prediction market=
 consisting only of (1) insiders and (2) outsiders who know they are bettin=
g against insiders but have reason to believe that they have a better model=
.
Last year I  wrote about Manifold Markets, =E2=80=9Ca sort-of-play-money pr=
ediction market that allows people to propose questions and bet on the answ=
ers.=E2=80=9D Specifically, there was a market on Manifold about whether I =
would mention Manifold. I wrote:
The odds when I looked yesterday were about 40%. The odds at 11:30 a.m. tod=
ay were 84%. The odds when I publish this will, of course, be 100%. Did I i=
nsider trade on this market? No. Was I tempted? For pedagogical and comedic=
 purposes, I mean, not to win play money? A little.
But of course the person who=C2=A0emailed=C2=A0me about the market=C2=A0sur=
ely=C2=A0insider traded: He knew he had emailed me, so he knew I had seen i=
t, so he knew the odds had increased. Perhaps=C2=A0he =E2=80=9Cinsider trad=
ed,=E2=80=9D in the sense that he knew something nonpublic and traded=C2=A0=
based on it, or perhaps he =E2=80=9Cmanipulated the market,=E2=80=9D in the=
 sense that he traded in the prediction market and then took steps in the r=
eal world (emailing me) to make his trade pay off.
After I wrote that paragraph, several people emailed me to be like =E2=80=
=9Cno, it=E2=80=99s cool, Manifold specifically encourages insider trading.=
=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s true: =E2=80=9CUnlike many other places,=E2=80=9D sa=
y Manifold=E2=80=99s=C2=A0community guidelines,=C2=A0=E2=80=9CManifold enco=
urages you to make markets more accurate by trading based on private inform=
ation you might have.=E2=80=9D Worse for fairness but better for accuracy, =
and they prefer accuracy.
But also, I mean, that particular case =E2=80=94=C2=A0me=C2=A0writing about=
 Manifold Markets =E2=80=94=C2=A0was not a particularly important event in =
the world. That was not the outcome of a presidential election or something=
. Nobody needed an accurate prediction of whether I would write about Manif=
old; no one was making business decisions based on that probability. That w=
as a small dumb possibility=C2=A0that became more likely because there was =
betting on it. It was possible to bet on me writing about Manifold, so peop=
le did, so someone emailed me to be like =E2=80=9Clol you should write abou=
t this,=E2=80=9D so I did. The existence of the prediction market called fo=
rth the event.
One worry that people have about prediction markets is that they will call =
forth events. Those events might be bad: If you can bet on terrorist attack=
s, terrorism might become profitable, which is a bad outcome. Also, though,=
 prediction markets =E2=80=94=C2=A0and, more broadly, widely available prop=
osition betting, sportsbooks offering bets on weird stuff=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=
=A0might just call forth more=C2=A0weird=C2=A0events. If you can bet on som=
e long-shot event happening, and then make it happen, somebody will. Partic=
ularly if it is relatively harmless and effortless.
Leading up to the Super Bowl, there were=C2=A0a lot of news stories about h=
ow sportsbooks were offering various Taylor Swift-related proposition bets.=
 The New York Times  quoted one bookmaker saying =E2=80=9CYou can ask me th=
e next day who won the game, and I won=E2=80=99t even know. But I=E2=80=99l=
l know how many times Taylor Swift was shown on TV.=E2=80=9D But  Bloomberg=
=E2=80=99s Ira Boudway pointed out on Friday that those sportsbooks are not=
 exactly=C2=A0allowed to offer those prop bets in the US:

=E2=80=9CThere are no states that have approved bets related to Taylor Swif=
t for the Super Bowl,=E2=80=9D says Cait DeBaun, a spokesperson for the Ame=
rican Gaming Association, which advocates for the casino industry. =E2=80=
=9CIf you=E2=80=99re seeing a website offering them, it=E2=80=99s an illega=
l offshore website that is not overseen by any US regulator.=E2=80=9D =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0
Offshore books exist in a legal gray area: They=E2=80=99re headquartered in=
 jurisdictions where their activity is legal but take bets from places wher=
e it=E2=80=99s not. ...
Gambling regulators in every state limit the scope of this betting to the a=
ction on the field. Books can take bets on how many touchdowns [Travis] Kel=
ce will score but not whether he will be shown kissing Swift. The reason is=
 to avoid bets that can be easily manipulated. Swift and Kelce, after all, =
could arrange ahead of time whether or not to smooch on the field. And if t=
hey do, producers for CBS=E2=80=94which is airing the game=E2=80=94would ha=
ve a say in whether to show it. =E2=80=9CWhen states legalized sports betti=
ng, they legalized sports betting, not betting on random events,=E2=80=9D D=
eBaun says.

Aww. I love the idea of Taylor Swift putting on a wig and a fake mustache a=
nd walking into a sportsbook to bet $10,000 on whether she=E2=80=99ll be sh=
own on TV kissing Travis Kelce. She is probably not economically incentiviz=
ed to manipulate that market. But the producers cutting between shots? Mayb=
e. If you have enough prop bets, somebody will have the right incentives to=
 manipulate them.
So here=E2=80=99s a funny TikTok from a guy pretending that he was =E2=80=
=9Cthe Super Bowl streaker,=E2=80=9D for arbitrage reasons:
I live here in Vegas and when I saw that you could bet on whether or not th=
ere would be a streaker during the Super Bowl, I knew=C2=A0I had to go down=
 to the casino and place a $20,000 bet. After I placed the bet, I went and =
bought a ticket for $10,000 so that I could control my own destiny. =E2=80=
=A6=C2=A0It was honestly totally worth it, I spent $10,000 on the ticket bu=
t I made 20 back on the wager, so I=E2=80=99m up $10,000. Yeah I had to spe=
nd a night in jail but I absolutely had a ball being center stage in front =
of 80,000 people.
I don=E2=80=99t think this is true; he seems to be a=C2=A0TikTok comedian a=
nd doesn=E2=80=99t appear to be one of the actual streakers at Sunday=E2=80=
=99s Super Bowl. But the math kind of works? An online sportsbook did appar=
ently offer +300 odds=C2=A0(a $100 bet returns $400) on =E2=80=9Cunauthoriz=
ed person will enter field of play,=E2=80=9D so you could bet $5,000, pay $=
10,000 for the ticket, run onto the field and make a profit. The more peopl=
e can bet on random events, the more random events there might be.

