   =20
      This meeting could have been an AI-generated summary
   =20
 =20

The basic question with the current crop of artificial intelligence tools i=
s: Will they automate the less valuable parts of white-collar jobs, allowin=
g lots of knowledge=C2=A0workers to be more productive and do more interest=
ing work? Or will they automate the=C2=A0most=C2=A0valuable parts of white-=
collar jobs, or all the parts, putting employees out of work or reducing th=
em to executing the machines=E2=80=99 instructions?
For instance, there=C2=A0is a standard view that large language models will=
 be able to replace some of the work of hedge fund analysts, giving portfol=
io managers the ability to generate and test and analyze more ideas and do =
their jobs better. But we   talked yesterday about a hedge fund that plans =
to employ human analysts to generate ideas,  but then =E2=80=9Ca systematic=
 algorithm will create a portfolio based on the ideas.=E2=80=9D You automat=
e out the boss who makes the final decision, but you=C2=A0keep the human gr=
unt workers who provide the inputs to that decision.
Anyway here is a fun  Wall Street Journal article about how =E2=80=9CEarly =
Adopters of Microsoft=E2=80=99s AI Bot Wonder If It=E2=80=99s Worth the Mon=
ey.=E2=80=9D Apparently some early testers have been unimpressed by how muc=
h value they can get out of Copilot for Microsoft 365, the AI plug-in for M=
icrosoft office software. It does not seem particularly close to replacing,=
 say, an investment banking analyst:

Testers said Excel was one of the programs on which they were less likely t=
o use the AI assistant because asking it to crunch numbers sometimes genera=
ted mistakes.=C2=A0 =E2=80=A6
Other features that Microsoft has touted, including the ability for Copilot=
 to generate PowerPoint slides, have also been disappointing, some users sa=
id.
Guido Appenzeller, a partner at investment firm Andreessen Horowitz, posted=
 a thread on X showing the mistakes it makes when prompted to make a presen=
tation.

There are a lot of jobs where the main functions are =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t=
 make mistakes in Excel or PowerPoint,=E2=80=9D so this is not that helpful=
. On the other hand, Copilot is apparently excellent at enabling another im=
portant skill for knowledge professionals, which is skipping large meetings=
 without guilt:

Early testers who spoke with The Wall Street Journal said the AI add-ons fo=
r Microsoft=E2=80=99s workplace communication software Teams were most usef=
ul.
Some had already become reliant on Copilot if they were late to a meeting, =
to get a summary of what had been said. Those in different countries and ti=
me zones now have the option to skip meetings and just read summaries.
=E2=80=9CIt has allowed people to say, =E2=80=98You know what, there is alr=
eady 10 other people on the call. I=E2=80=99m going to skip this one. I=E2=
=80=99m going to catch up in the morning by reading the digest and skipping=
 to the parts of the meeting I really needed to hear,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D sai=
d Art Hu, the global chief information officer at Lenovo.=C2=A0

Yes, it has allowed them to=C2=A0say=C2=A0that they=E2=80=99ll skip the mee=
ting and then read the digest. I suspect it also allows them to skip the di=
gest. Also the digest is wrong:

At one ad agency, a Copilot-generated summary of a meeting once said that =
=E2=80=9CBob=E2=80=9D spoke about =E2=80=9Cproduct strategy.=E2=80=9D
The problem was that no one named Bob was on the call and no one spoke abou=
t product strategy, an executive at the company said.=C2=A0

Yeah, but you see how that happened, right? If I told you =E2=80=9Cwrite a =
summary of a meeting at an ad agency,=E2=80=9D you=E2=80=99d probably inclu=
de the sentence =E2=80=9CBob spoke about product strategy=E2=80=9D too. May=
be even if you went to the meeting! You probably weren=E2=80=99t paying att=
ention the whole time either; the AI model can half-listen to the meeting j=
ust as well as you can. Large language models are not in the business of in=
terpreting reality and summarizing it accurately; they=E2=80=99re in the bu=
siness of completing texts in plausible=C2=A0ways. That is a risky approach=
 to financial modeling but=C2=A0an incredibly efficient=C2=A0approach to su=
mmarizing meetings.
Elsewhere: =E2=80=9CAI Is Starting to Threaten White-Collar Jobs. Few Indus=
tries Are Immune.=E2=80=9D

 =20
   =20
      PE pay for performance
   =20
 =20

We  talked the other day about Carlyle Group Inc.=E2=80=99s plan to pay its=
 employees more out of performance fees (which vary from year to year depen=
ding on how successfully Carlyle=E2=80=99s funds exit their investments) an=
d less out of management fees (which are pretty stable from year to year). =
My point was that there is a sort of arbitrage: Carlyle=E2=80=99s=C2=A0shar=
eholders=C2=A0prefer stable recurring fees, so they place a higher multiple=
 on the management fees than the performance fees, while Carlyle=E2=80=99s =
employees=C2=A0really ought to be motivated to deliver good performance, so=
 Carlyle should pay them mostly out of performance fees. It=E2=80=99s a win=
-win: Give the shareholders the management fees to satisfy their desire for=
 stability, and give the employees the performance fees to motivate them.
But of course there was a bit of sleight of hand in that argument: Carlyle=
=E2=80=99s shareholders=C2=A0value=C2=A0stable management fees more, I said=
, while Carlyle=E2=80=99s employees are=C2=A0motivated=C2=A0by variable per=
formance fees. Those things are not parallel. It=E2=80=99s not a real arbit=
rage. Carlyle=E2=80=99s shareholders value stable income more than risky pe=
rformance, and Carlyle=E2=80=99s employees=C2=A0also=C2=A0probably value st=
able income more than risky performance. They don=E2=80=99t want to be moti=
vated! They want to be paid. If you=E2=80=99re taking some stable managemen=
t fees away from the employees, and replacing them with at-risk performance=
 fees, you have to give the employees=C2=A0more to make it worth their whil=
e.
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s  Dawn Lim ran the numbers for Carlyle (and also KKR & C=
o., which has made similar changes):

Staff across Carlyle and KKR would have earned some $170 million less last =
year had the changes already been in place, Bloomberg calculations show. To=
tal pay would have expanded in 2021 and 2022 by roughly $300 million. =E2=
=80=A6
=E2=80=9CThis is not about changing the overall level of compensation,=E2=
=80=9D Carlyle=E2=80=99s new finance chief, John Redett, told analysts. It=
=E2=80=99s about having a higher chunk of pay driven by performance, he sai=
d.
The moves push more volatility in profits from shareholders to employees.
If Carlyle=E2=80=99s new pay system had been rolled out years ago, employee=
s would have made about $190 million =E2=80=94 some 8% =E2=80=94 more in 20=
21, and roughly $40 million =E2=80=94 about 2% more in 2022, according to B=
loomberg estimates. KKR employees would have made an extra $20 million or 1=
% of pay in 2021.

You have to pay them $300 million more in the good years to make up for pay=
ing them $170 million less in the bad years. It=E2=80=99s still a good arbi=
trage if the shareholders value stability=C2=A0more=C2=A0than the dealmaker=
s do, which seems plausible.
  [1]
 But the dealmakers do value stability.

 =20
   =20
      Indian options trading
   =20
 =20

In general, if someone tells you that they know how to make a fortune tradi=
ng in the stock market, and that, for a fee,=C2=A0they will use that skill =
to make=C2=A0you=C2=A0a fortune in the stock market (or to teach you how to=
 make a fortune), you should ask: Why? What=E2=80=99s in it for them? They =
can just make money for themselves in the stock market; why do they need yo=
ur=C2=A0money?
Sometimes there is a satisfactory answer. We   talked yesterday about multi=
strategy hedge funds, which have a pretty good reputation these days, and w=
hich answer the question by saying =E2=80=9Cwe will take 59 cents of every =
dollar that we generate with your money.=E2=80=9D What=E2=80=99s their ince=
ntive to make profits for you in the stock market? They take most of the pr=
ofits! Very satisfactory answer.
  [2]

But a lot of the time, particularly if they are advertising investing cours=
es to retail investors on social media, the answer is pretty obviously that=
 they=C2=A0can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0make a fortune in the stock market, but they=
=C2=A0can=C2=A0make a fortune by persuading you to give them your money. He=
re=E2=80=99s a   Bloomberg News story about retail options trading in India=
, which is mostly hopeless gambling:

=E2=80=9CIf you want to gamble, if you need diabetes and high blood pressur=
e, then go into this market,=E2=80=9D Ashwani Bhatia, a board member on the=
 nation=E2=80=99s top stock market regulator, said last year.
His agency, the Securities and Exchange Board of India, known as Sebi, says=
 90% of active retail traders lose money trading options and other derivati=
ve contracts. In the year ended March 2022, the latest for which figures ar=
e available, investors lost $5.4 billion.

But there are a lot of options-trading promoters who will, for a fee, teach=
 you how to do it:
Like a movie star at a premiere, Mohammad Nasiruddin Ansari steps out of th=
e back seat of a white Mercedes. Flanked by a phalanx of black-clad bodygua=
rds, he strides into the lobby of a luxury hotel and takes center stage in =
a ballroom as indoor fireworks machines spew fountains of sparks. =E2=80=9C=
If you don=E2=80=99t make money in three months, I will give you 2 million =
rupees [$24,000],=E2=80=9D he declares to cheers from the adoring crowd in =
a scene that=E2=80=99s still playing on YouTube.
But they are lying:

Sebi took action against Ansari in October, citing him for improperly promo=
ting himself as a stock market expert, promising near-certain profits and a=
cting as an unregistered investment adviser. The agency ordered him and an =
associate to refund 172 million rupees they=E2=80=99d charged for online tr=
aining courses. Ansari and his company didn=E2=80=99t respond to messages s=
eeking comment.
Sebi examined Ansari=E2=80=99s personal brokerage account to reveal how suc=
cessful he was in his own trading. Regulators tallied up the results from J=
anuary to July 2023. Ansari lost $347,695.

He lost $347,695 trading and made 172 million rupees (roughly $2 million) s=
elling courses. Good trade, for him, until he had to give the fees back.
I have to say, I love the regulatory strategy of just reporting the actual =
trading results of online trading influencers? Sebi must have had fun readi=
ng those brokerage statements. I feel like the US Securities and Exchange C=
ommission should do that. Like if you sell investment courses and post onli=
ne about your trades, the SEC should just reply to all of your posts =E2=80=
=9Cyou lost $37,000 last month and have never been profitable.=E2=80=9D Dis=
pel the mystique a little.

