rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
solid; background-color: #ccc;">prediction<em>=C2=A0</em>markets</a> are mo=
re likely to<em>=C2=A0</em><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/34337106.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly9tYXNvbi5nbXUuZWR1L35yaGFuc29uL2luc2lkZX=
JiZXQucGRm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa74f7b14" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">argue</a> that inside=
r trading is good. The point of a prediction market is not really to give p=
eople a good place to invest their retirement money; the point of a predict=
ion market is to make accurate predictions. In the stock market, you=C2=A0w=
ant<em>=C2=A0</em>outsiders to feel comfortable that they can invest their =
money and have a fair chance, and you might think that=E2=80=99s=C2=A0more =
important than price accuracy. In a prediction market, you don=E2=80=99t re=
ally care about fairness to outsiders at all; your goal is to get a good pr=
ediction. You=E2=80=99d be totally happy with a prediction market consistin=
g only of (1) insiders and (2) outsiders who know they are betting against =
insiders but have reason to believe that they have a better model.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Last year I <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/34337106.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9v=
cGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMjEvb3BlbmFpLWlzLWEtc3RyYW5nZS1ub25wcm9maXQ=
