5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjEzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ce=
ef4b8524a319a23cBbe759f67" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" t=
arget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important;=
 border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-styl=
e: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wrote about Manifold Markets</a>, =E2=
=80=9Ca sort-of-play-money prediction market that allows people to propose =
questions and bet on the answers.=E2=80=9D Specifically, there was a market=
 on Manifold about whether I would mention Manifold. I wrote:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The odds when I looked yesterday w=
ere about 40%. The odds at 11:30 a.m. today were 84%. The odds when I publi=
sh this will, of course, be 100%. Did I insider trade on this market? No. W=
as I tempted? For pedagogical and comedic purposes, I mean, not to win play=
 money? A little.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But of course the person who=C2=A0<em>emailed=
=C2=A0</em>me about the market=C2=A0<em>surely=C2=A0</em>insider traded: He=
 knew he had emailed me, so he knew I had seen it, so he knew the odds had =
increased. Perhaps=C2=A0he =E2=80=9Cinsider traded,=E2=80=9D in the sense t=
hat he knew something nonpublic and traded=C2=A0based on it, or perhaps he =
=E2=80=9Cmanipulated the market,=E2=80=9D in the sense that he traded in th=
e prediction market and then took steps in the real world (emailing me) to =
make his trade pay off.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">After I wrote that paragraph, several people e=
mailed me to be like =E2=80=9Cno, it=E2=80=99s cool, Manifold specifically =
encourages insider trading.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s true: =E2=80=9CUnlike man=
y other places,=E2=80=9D say Manifold=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://lin=
k.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34337106.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly9tYW5pZm9sZG1h=
cmtldHMubm90aW9uLnNpdGUvT2xkLUNvbW11bml0eS1HdWlkZWxpbmVzLWY2Yzc3YjFhZjQxNzQ=
5ODI4ZGY3ZGFlNWU4NzM1NDAw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB7d2e06a5" itemprop=3D"St=
oryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000;=
 text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-=
color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">commun=
ity guidelines</a>,=C2=A0=E2=80=9CManifold <em>encourages</em> you to make =
markets more accurate by trading based on private information you might hav=
e.=E2=80=9D Worse for fairness but better for accuracy, and they prefer acc=
uracy.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But also, I mean, that particular case =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0me=C2=A0writing about Manifold Markets =E2=80=94=C2=A0was not a pa=
rticularly important event in the world. That was not the outcome of a pres=
idential election or something. Nobody needed an accurate prediction of whe=
ther I would write about Manifold; no one was making business decisions bas=
ed on that probability. That was a small dumb possibility=C2=A0that <em>bec=
ame more likely because there was betting on it</em>. It was possible to be=
t on me writing about Manifold, so people did, so someone emailed me to be =
like =E2=80=9Clol you should write about this,=E2=80=9D so I did. The exist=
ence of the prediction market called forth the event.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One worry that people have about prediction ma=
rkets is that they will call forth events. Those events might be bad: If yo=
u can bet on terrorist attacks, terrorism might become profitable, which is=
 a bad outcome. Also, though, prediction markets =E2=80=94=C2=A0and, more b=
roadly, widely available proposition betting, sportsbooks offering bets on =
weird stuff=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0might just call forth more=C2=A0<em>weird=
=C2=A0</em>events. If you can bet on some long-shot event happening, and th=
en make it happen, somebody will. Particularly if it is relatively harmless=
 and effortless.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Leading up to the Super Bowl, there were=C2=A0=
a lot of news stories about how sportsbooks were offering various Taylor Sw=
ift-related proposition bets. The New York Times <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34337106.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cubnl0aW1lcy5j=
b20vMjAyNC8wMi8wNS9zdHlsZS90YXlsb3Itc3dpZnQtc3VwZXItYm93bC1wcm9wLWJldHMuaHR=
tbA/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB494a0041" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"=
itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none=
 !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border=
-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> quoted one bookmaker</a> sa=
ying =E2=80=9CYou can ask me the next day who won the game, and I won=E2=80=
=99t even know. But I=E2=80=99ll know how many times Taylor Swift was shown=
 on TV.=E2=80=9D But <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/34337106.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIw=
MjQtMDItMDkvdGF5bG9yLXN3aWZ0LXRyYXZpcy1rZWxjZS1hZGQtYS10d2lzdC10by1zdXBlci1=
ib3dsLXByb3AtYmV0cz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjEzMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYW=
lsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAyMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vb=
mV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB342da269" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Bloomberg=E2=80=99s =
Ira Boudway pointed out</a> on Friday that those sportsbooks are not exactl=
y=C2=A0allowed to offer those prop bets in the US:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThere are no states that have approve=
d bets related to Taylor Swift for the Super Bowl,=E2=80=9D says Cait DeBau=
n, a spokesperson for the American Gaming Association, which advocates for =
the casino industry. =E2=80=9CIf you=E2=80=99re seeing a website offering t=
hem, it=E2=80=99s an illegal offshore website that is not overseen by any U=
S regulator.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Offshore books exist in a legal gray area: The=
y=E2=80=99re headquartered in jurisdictions where their activity is legal b=
ut take bets from places where it=E2=80=99s not. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Gambling regulators in every state limit the s=
cope of this betting to the action on the field. Books can take bets on how=
 many touchdowns [Travis] Kelce will score but not whether he will be shown=
 kissing Swift. The reason is to avoid bets that can be easily manipulated.=
 Swift and Kelce, after all, could arrange ahead of time whether or not to =
smooch on the field. And if they do, producers for CBS=E2=80=94which is air=
ing the game=E2=80=94would have a say in whether to show it. =E2=80=9CWhen =
states legalized sports betting, they legalized sports betting, not betting=
 on random events,=E2=80=9D DeBaun says.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Aww. I love the idea of Taylor Swift putting o=
n a wig and a fake mustache and walking into a sportsbook to bet $10,000 on=
 whether she=E2=80=99ll be shown on TV kissing Travis Kelce. <em>She</em> i=
s probably not economically incentivized to manipulate that market. But the=
 producers cutting between shots? Maybe. If you have enough prop bets, some=
body will have the right incentives to manipulate them.</p>
