<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">This meeting could have been an AI-generated summary</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic question with the current crop of ar=
tificial intelligence tools is: Will they automate the less valuable parts =
of white-collar jobs, allowing lots of knowledge=C2=A0workers to be more pr=
oductive and do more interesting work? Or will they automate the=C2=A0<em>m=
ost=C2=A0</em>valuable parts of white-collar jobs, or all the parts, puttin=
g employees out of work or reducing them to executing the machines=E2=80=99=
 instructions?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">For instance, there=C2=A0is a standard view th=
at large language models will be able to replace some of the work of hedge =
fund analysts, giving portfolio managers the ability to generate and test a=
nd analyze more ideas and do their jobs better. But we <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34337106.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb2=
1iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMTIvd2hhdC1pZi10ZXNsYS1jYW4td=
C1sZWF2ZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjEzMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9z=
b3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAyMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY=
/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd72119c4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"ite=
mscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !i=
mportant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bo=
ttom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked yesterday</a> about a =
hedge fund that plans to employ human analysts to generate ideas, <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34337106.258392/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYnVzaW5lc3NpbnNpZGVyLmNvbS9ub3JpYXMtcmVzZWFyY2gtbGF1bmNoLXN0cmF0ZWd5=
LWZlZXMtMjAyNC0y/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB2436bfdd" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> but then</a> =
=E2=80=9Ca systematic algorithm will create a portfolio based on the ideas.=
=E2=80=9D You automate out the boss who makes the final decision, but you=
=C2=A0keep the human grunt workers who provide the inputs to that decision.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway here is a fun <a href=3D"https://link.m=
ail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34337106.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9=
0ZWNoL2FpL2Vhcmx5LWFkb3B0ZXJzLW9mLW1pY3Jvc29mdHMtYWktYm90LXdvbmRlci1pZi1pdH=
Mtd29ydGgtdGhlLW1vbmV5LTJlNzRlM2EyP21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3BvczU/607f07ceef4b8524a=
319a23cB1d536051" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"=
_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid;=
 background-color: #ccc;"> Wall Street Journal article</a> about how =E2=80=
=9CEarly Adopters of Microsoft=E2=80=99s AI Bot Wonder If It=E2=80=99s Wort=
h the Money.=E2=80=9D Apparently some early testers have been unimpressed b=
y how much value they can get out of Copilot for Microsoft 365, the AI plug=
-in for Microsoft office software. It does not seem particularly close to r=
eplacing, say, an investment banking analyst:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Testers said Excel was one of the programs on =
which they were less likely to use the AI assistant because asking it to cr=
unch numbers sometimes generated mistakes.=C2=A0 =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Other features that Microsoft has touted, incl=
uding the ability for Copilot to generate PowerPoint slides, have also been=
 disappointing, some users said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Guido Appenzeller, a partner at investment fir=
m Andreessen Horowitz, posted a thread on X showing the mistakes it makes w=
hen prompted to make a presentation.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">There are a lot of jobs where the main functio=
ns are =E2=80=9Cdon=E2=80=99t make mistakes in Excel or PowerPoint,=E2=80=
=9D so this is not that helpful. On the other hand, Copilot is apparently e=
xcellent at enabling another important skill for knowledge professionals, w=
hich is skipping large meetings without guilt:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Early testers who spoke with The Wall Street J=
ournal said the AI add-ons for Microsoft=E2=80=99s workplace communication =
software Teams were most useful.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Some had already become reliant on Copilot if =
they were late to a meeting, to get a summary of what had been said. Those =
in different countries and time zones now have the option to skip meetings =
and just read summaries.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIt has allowed people to say, =E2=80=
=98You know what, there is already 10 other people on the call. I=E2=80=99m=
 going to skip this one. I=E2=80=99m going to catch up in the morning by re=
ading the digest and skipping to the parts of the meeting I really needed t=
o hear,=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D said Art Hu, the global chief information officer=
 at Lenovo.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yes, it has allowed them to=C2=A0<em>say=C2=A0=
</em>that they=E2=80=99ll skip the meeting and then read the digest. I susp=
ect it also allows them to skip the digest. Also the digest is wrong:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At one ad agency, a Copilot-generated summary =
of a meeting once said that =E2=80=9CBob=E2=80=9D spoke about =E2=80=9Cprod=
uct strategy.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The problem was that no one named Bob was on t=
he call and no one spoke about product strategy, an executive at the compan=
y said.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Yeah, but you see how that happened, right? If=
 I told you =E2=80=9Cwrite a summary of a meeting at an ad agency,=E2=80=9D=
 you=E2=80=99d probably include the sentence =E2=80=9CBob spoke about produ=
ct strategy=E2=80=9D too. Maybe even if you went to the meeting! You probab=
ly weren=E2=80=99t paying attention the whole time either; the AI model can=
 half-listen to the meeting just as well as you can. Large language models =
are not in the business of interpreting reality and summarizing it accurate=
ly; they=E2=80=99re in the business of completing texts in plausible=C2=A0w=
ays. That is a risky approach to financial modeling but=C2=A0an <em>incredi=
bly efficient=C2=A0</em>approach to summarizing meetings.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Elsewhere: =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34337106.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9s=
aWZlc3R5bGUvY2FyZWVycy9haS1pcy1zdGFydGluZy10by10aHJlYXRlbi13aGl0ZS1jb2xsYXI=
tam9icy1mZXctaW5kdXN0cmllcy1hcmUtaW1tdW5lLTljZGJjYjkwP21vZD1ocF9saXN0YV9wb3=
Mx/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB6ac19d2a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">AI Is Starting to Threaten Wh=
ite-Collar Jobs</a>. Few Industries Are Immune.=E2=80=9D</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">PE pay for performance</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/34337106.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMDcvaGVkZ2UtZnVuZHMtYXJlLWRlYWxlcnMtbm93P2NtcGlkPUJC=
RDAyMTMyNF9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGV=
yJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MDIxMyZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a31=
9a23cBfe07d470" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_b=
lank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bot=
tom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; b=
ackground-color: #ccc;"> talked the other day</a> about Carlyle Group Inc.=
=E2=80=99s plan to pay its employees more out of performance fees (which va=
ry from year to year depending on how successfully Carlyle=E2=80=99s funds =
exit their investments) and less out of management fees (which are pretty s=
table from year to year). My point was that there is a sort of arbitrage: C=
arlyle=E2=80=99s=C2=A0<em>shareholders=C2=A0</em>prefer stable recurring fe=
es, so they place a higher multiple on the management fees than the perform=
ance fees, while Carlyle=E2=80=99s <em>employees=C2=A0</em>really ought to =
be motivated to deliver good performance, so Carlyle should pay them mostly=
 out of performance fees. It=E2=80=99s a win-win: Give the shareholders the=
 management fees to satisfy their desire for stability, and give the employ=
ees the performance fees to motivate them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But of course there was a bit of sleight of ha=
nd in that argument: Carlyle=E2=80=99s shareholders=C2=A0<em>value=C2=A0</e=
m>stable management fees more, I said, while Carlyle=E2=80=99s employees ar=
e=C2=A0<em>motivated=C2=A0</em>by variable performance fees. Those things a=
re not parallel. It=E2=80=99s not a real arbitrage. Carlyle=E2=80=99s share=
holders value stable income more than risky performance, and Carlyle=E2=80=
=99s employees=C2=A0<em>also=C2=A0</em>probably value stable income more th=
an risky performance. They don=E2=80=99t want to be motivated! They want to=
 be paid. If you=E2=80=99re taking some stable management fees away from th=
e employees, and replacing them with at-risk performance fees, you have to =
give the employees=C2=A0more to make it worth their while.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.ma=
il.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34337106.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJn=
LmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMTIvY2FybHlsZS1ra3ItcmFpc2UtdGhlLXN0YWt=
lcy1mb3ItcmFpbm1ha2Vycy10by1kZWxpdmVyLXJldHVybnM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxMzI0X01PTk=
VZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09M=
jQwMjEzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB007f6af6" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;"> Dawn Lim ran the numbers</a> for Carlyle (and also KKR &amp; Co., =
which has made similar changes):</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Staff across Carlyle and KKR would have earned=
 some $170 million less last year had the changes already been in place, Bl=
oomberg calculations show. Total pay would have expanded in 2021 and 2022 b=
y roughly $300 million. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis is not about changing the overal=
l level of compensation,=E2=80=9D Carlyle=E2=80=99s new finance chief, John=
 Redett, told analysts. It=E2=80=99s about having a higher chunk of pay dri=
ven by performance, he said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The moves push more volatility in profits from=
 shareholders to employees.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If Carlyle=E2=80=99s new pay system had been r=
olled out years ago, employees would have made about $190 million =E2=80=94=
 some 8% =E2=80=94 more in 2021, and roughly $40 million =E2=80=94 about 2%=
 more in 2022, according to Bloomberg estimates. KKR employees would have m=
ade an extra $20 million or 1% of pay in 2021.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You have to pay them $300 million more in the =
good years to make up for paying them $170 million less in the bad years. I=
t=E2=80=99s still a good arbitrage if the shareholders value stability=C2=
=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>than the dealmakers do, which seems plausible.<a clas=
s=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent =
!important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> But the dealmakers do value stability.</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Indian options trading</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In general, if someone tells you that they kno=
w how to make a fortune trading in the stock market, and that, for a fee,=
=C2=A0they will use that skill to make=C2=A0<em>you=C2=A0</em>a fortune in =
the stock market (or to teach you how to make a fortune), you should ask: W=
hy? What=E2=80=99s in it for them? They can just make money for themselves =
in the stock market; why do they need <em>your=C2=A0</em>money?</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sometimes there is a satisfactory answer. We <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34337106.258392/aHR=
0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMTIvd2hhdC=
1pZi10ZXNsYS1jYW4tdC1sZWF2ZT9jbXBpZD1CQkQwMjEzMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVka=
XVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDAyMTMmdXRtX2NhbXBh=
aWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCd72119c4" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  talked yes=
terday</a> about multistrategy hedge funds, which have a pretty good reputa=
tion these days, and which answer the question by saying =E2=80=9Cwe will t=
ake 59 cents of every dollar that we generate with your money.=E2=80=9D Wha=
t=E2=80=99s their incentive to make profits for you in the stock market? Th=
ey take most of the profits! Very satisfactory answer.<a class=3D"footnote-=
index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; di=
splay: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But a lot of the time, particularly if they ar=
e advertising investing courses to retail investors on social media, the an=
swer is pretty obviously that they=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>make a =
fortune in the stock market, but they=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>make a fortune=
 by persuading you to give them your money. Here=E2=80=99s a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34337106.258392/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
Ymxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2ZlYXR1cmVzLzIwMjQtMDItMTMvaW5kaWEtcy1vcHRpb25zLXR=
yYWRpbmctYm9vbS1oaWRlcy1iaWxsaW9ucy1vZi1sb3NzZXMtZm9yLXJldGFpbC1pbnZlc3Rvcn=
M_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIxMzI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlP=
W5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjEzJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07c=
eef4b8524a319a23cB2546d14e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" =
target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important=
; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-sty=
le: solid; background-color: #ccc;">  Bloomberg News story</a> about retail=
 options trading in India, which is mostly hopeless gambling:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIf you want to gamble, if you need di=
abetes and high blood pressure, then go into this market,=E2=80=9D Ashwani =
Bhatia, a board member on the nation=E2=80=99s top stock market regulator, =
said last year.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">His agency, the Securities and Exchange Board =
of India, known as Sebi, says 90% of active retail traders lose money tradi=
ng options and other derivative contracts. In the year ended March 2022, th=
e latest for which figures are available, investors lost $5.4 billion.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there are a lot of options-trading promote=
rs who will, for a fee, teach you how to do it:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Like a movie star at a premiere, M=
ohammad Nasiruddin Ansari steps out of the back seat of a white Mercedes. F=
lanked by a phalanx of black-clad bodyguards, he strides into the lobby of =
a luxury hotel and takes center stage in a ballroom as indoor fireworks mac=
hines spew fountains of sparks. =E2=80=9CIf you don=E2=80=99t make money in=
 three months, I will give you 2 million rupees [$24,000],=E2=80=9D he decl=
ares to cheers from the adoring crowd in a scene that=E2=80=99s still playi=
ng on YouTube.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But they are lying:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sebi took action against Ansari in October, ci=
ting him for improperly promoting himself as a stock market expert, promisi=
ng near-certain profits and acting as an unregistered investment adviser. T=
he agency ordered him and an associate to refund 172 million rupees they=E2=
=80=99d charged for online training courses. Ansari and his company didn=E2=
=80=99t respond to messages seeking comment.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sebi examined Ansari=E2=80=99s personal broker=
age account to reveal how successful he was in his own trading. Regulators =
tallied up the results from January to July 2023. Ansari lost $347,695.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">He lost $347,695 trading and made 172 million =
rupees (roughly $2 million) selling courses. Good trade, for him, until he =
had to give the fees back.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have to say, I love the regulatory strategy =
of just reporting the actual trading results of online trading influencers?=
 Sebi must have had fun reading those brokerage statements. I feel like the=
 US Securities and Exchange Commission should do that. Like if you sell inv=
estment courses and post online about your trades, the SEC should just repl=
y to all of your posts =E2=80=9Cyou lost $37,000 last month and have never =
been profitable.=E2=80=9D Dispel the mystique a little.</p>
